{"title_page": "Sports broadcasting contracts in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{further|List of sports television broadcast contracts}}\n{{short description|List explaining current sports broadcasting rights in the UK}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\nIn the United Kingdom, [[broadcasting of sports events|sporting events are broadcast]] on several national television networks, as well as radio. \n\nCertain sporting events are protected by the [[Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events]] and must be broadcast live and [[free-to-air]] on [[terrestrial television]] in the UK.\n\nPresently, free-to-air means a TV channel which is free and covers 98% of the population.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/10/parliament-future-world-cups-free-to-air-tv |title=Parliament to discuss keeping future World Cups on free-to-air TV |date=10 July 2018 }}</ref> According to Ofcom regulations, qualifying free-to-air channels are [[BBC One]], [[BBC Two]], [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], [[Channel 4]] and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]].\n\n==Association football==\n===Television===\n{{see also|English football on television}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" width=1000px\n|+Broadcasting contracts for football (television) \u2013 International matches\n!width=35%|Event\n!width=15%|Broadcasters (free-to-air)\n!width=15%|Broadcasters (paid)\n!width=15%|[[Ofcom]]\n!width=50%|Broadcast details\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | FIFA World Cup\n| BBC\n| rowspan=\"2\" | None\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{yes2}} [[Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events#Category A|Category A]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | All matches live on BBC & ITV with final live on both broadcasters in [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27750996 |title=BBC and ITV win rights to 2018 and 2022 Fifa World Cup finals |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 June 2014 |accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ITV\n|-\n| rowspa